## Square difference between two vectors
diffSq<-function(x,y){
  (x-y)^2
}

## define sample variogram
expVar<-function(Z,n0,lag,nbpts,Nx,Ny,dx,dy){
  
  kech=sample(1:(Nx*Ny),n0)
  xech=((kech-1)%%Nx+1)*dx
  yech=((kech-1)%/%Nx+1)*dy
  nmax=min(length(xech),length(yech))
  xech=xech[1:nmax]
  yech=yech[1:nmax]
    
  dist=(sqrt(outer(xech,xech,diffSq)+outer(yech,yech,diffSq)))
  dist=dist[upper.tri(dist)]
  diffZ=(outer(Z[kech],Z[kech],diffSq))
  diffZ=diffZ[upper.tri(diffZ)]
  
  breaks=seq(from=0,by=lag,length.out = nbpts)
  lagcut=cut(dist, breaks=breaks, labels =FALSE)
  varexp=tapply(diffZ,lagcut,mean)/2
  return(cbind(lag=lag/2+(as.numeric(rownames(varexp))-1)*lag,varexp))
}

## Matérn covariance
Matern<-function(x,kappa,nu,cov=FALSE){
  if(cov) return((2^(1-nu)/gamma(nu))*(sqrt(2*nu)*kappa*x)^(nu)*besselK(sqrt(2*nu)*kappa*x,nu))
  else    return(1-(2^(1-nu)/gamma(nu))*(sqrt(2*nu)*kappa*x)^(nu)*besselK(sqrt(2*nu)*kappa*x,nu)) 
}

While most of Geostatistical estimation procedures suffer from severe limitations when considering large dimensions for both observation vector \(\mathbb{R}^p\) and state space \(\mathbb{R}^m\), the SPDE-based estimation model is a new formalism introduced by constrained by the use of Matèrn covariance model: \[\begin{align*} C(\mathbf{h})=\sigma^2\frac{2^{1-\nu}}{\Gamma(\nu)}\left(\sqrt{2\nu}\frac{h}{a}\right)^\nu \mathcal{K}_\nu\left(\sqrt{2\nu}\frac{h}{a}\right) \end{align*}\]

with:

  • \(h=|\mathbf{s}-\mathbf{s}'|\) is the distance between two spatial locations
  • \(\mathcal{K}_\nu\) is the modified 2nd order Bessel function
  • \(\nu\) controls the regularity of the covariance

Let note that for:

  • \(\nu=1/2\), we get the exponential covariance
  • \(\nu\rightarrow +\infty\), we get the gaussian covariance

If \(\mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s})\), $ ^d $, is a Gaussian random field (GRF) with Matern covariance having regularity parameters , scale parameter \(a\) and variance \(\sigma^2\), then \(\mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s})\) is solution of the following SPDE : \[\begin{align} \label{isotropic_SPDE} (\kappa^2 - \Delta)^{\alpha/2} \mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s}) = \tau\mathbf{Z}(\mathbf{s}) \end{align}\]

with:

  • \(\Delta = \sum_{i=1}^d \frac{\partial^2}{\partial s_i^2}\) the Laplacian
  • \(\mathbf{Z}(\mathbf{s})\) is standard Gaussian white noise
  • \(\kappa = 1/a\)
  • \(\alpha = \nu + d/2\)
  • \(\tau = \frac{\sigma\Gamma(\nu+d/2)^{1/2}(4\pi)^{d/4}\kappa^{\nu}}{\Gamma(\nu)^{1/2}}\)
plot(Matern(seq(0,50,.1),.2,10,cov=TRUE),col="red",type='l',ylim=c(0,1),ylab='C(h)',xlab='h')
lines(Matern(seq(0,50,.1),.2,1/2,cov=TRUE),col="blue",type='l')
legend('topright', legend=c("Gaussian", "Exponential"),col=c("red", "blue"), lty=1:2, cex=1.5,box.col=0)

lines(Matern(seq(0,50,.1),.2,1/2,cov=FALSE),col="blue",type='l')
legend('bottomright', legend=c("Gaussian", "Exponential"),col=c("red", "blue"), lty=1:2, cex=1.5,box.col=0)

## II. Spatial case

Let now consider state space \(\mathbf{x} \in \mathbb{R}^m\), which can be seen as a discretized version of process \(\mathbf{x}(\mathbf{s})\) on a regular grid of size \(m = N_x \times N_y\) with grid step \(dx\) and \(dy\). Then, an element of state space \(\mathbf{x}\) can be located on the grid either by its coordinates \((x, y)\) or by indices \((i, j)\) where \(i \in \lbrace{1, \cdots, N_x \rbrace}\) and \(j \in \lbrace{1,\cdots,N_y \rbrace}\).

A discretized version of SPDE on a grid node \((i, j)\) is: \[\begin{eqnarray*} \kappa^2-\Delta\mathbf{x}(i,j)=\tau \mathbf{z}(i,j) \end{eqnarray*}\] is obtained using a centered finite difference scheme of the Laplacian operator \(\Delta=\frac{\partial{}}{\partial{x}} + \frac{\partial{}}{\partial{y}}\). We will approach the partial derivative of \(\mathbf{x}\) with respect to coordinate \(y\) by a centered difference: \[\begin{eqnarray*} \frac{\partial \mathbf{x}}{\partial y}=\frac{\mathbf{x}(y+dy/2)-\mathbf{x}(y-dy/2)}{dx} \end{eqnarray*}\]

We get: \[\begin{eqnarray*} \kappa^2 \mathbf{x}(i,j) &-&\frac{\mathbf{x}(i-1,j)-2\mathbf{x}(i,j)+\mathbf{x}(i+1,j)}{dx^2} \\ &-& \frac{\mathbf{x}(i,j-1)-2\mathbf{x}(i,j)+\mathbf{x}(i,j+1)}{dy^2} = \mathbf{z}(i,j) \end{eqnarray*}\]

II.1 DF Discretized Laplacian

Let now write the discretized of version SPDE in matrix notations by using the vectors \(\mathbf{x}\) and \(\mathbf{z}\) and a matrix \(\mathbf{A}\) corresponding to the discretized version of fractional differential operator over the grid: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{A}\mathbf{x}=\tau\mathbf{z} \end{align*}\] or : * \(A_{i,j}\) = {\(-1/dx^2\)} if \(j=i+1\) or \(j=i-1\) * \(A_{i,j}\) = {\(-1/dy^2\)} if \(j=i+N_x\) or \(j=i-N_x\) * \(A_{i,j}\) = \(\kappa^2 + 2(1/dx^2+1/dy^2)\) if \(j=i\) * \(A_{i,j}\) = 0 otherwise

# Discretized Laplacian (differential operator)
## Inputs :  
## Nx : number of points in direction x
## Ny : number of points in direction y
## dx : lag in direction x
## dy : lag in direction y
## Results :
## Sparse matrix with size (Nx*Ny)x(Nx*Ny) 

DiffOperator<-function(Nx,Ny,dx,dy, kappa){
  
  nbNodes=Nx*Ny
  indices=1:nbNodes
  

  # We start by creating an array containing the indices of the non-zero elements
  # of A with associated values and we will use the R function sparseMatrix 
  # to create A from this array

  # Right neighbour ( !! remove last column)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==0)]
  # Matrix values
  k1=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+1, -1/dx^2)
  
  # Left neighbour ( !! remove first column)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==1)]
  # Matrix values
  k2=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-1, -1/dx^2)
  
  # Top neighbour  ( !! remove last line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices>(Ny-1)*Nx)]
  # Matrix values
  k3=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+Nx, -1/dy^2)
  
  # Bottom neighbour ( !! remove first line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices<Nx+1)]
  # Matrix values
  k4=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-Nx, -1/dy^2)
  
  # Central point
  k5=cbind(indices,indices,kappa^2+2*(1/dx^2+1/dy^2))

  # Stack all neighbours
  k=rbind(k1,k2,k3,k4,k5)
  
  # Create sparseMatrix
  return(sparseMatrix(i=k[,1],j=k[,2],x=k[,3],dims = c(nbNodes,nbNodes)))
  
}

# Test function
A=DiffOperator(10,10,1,1,0)
image(A)

## Degree of differential operator
pow_diff_operator<-function(A,pow){
    B=A
    if(pow>1){
      for(i in 1:(pow-1)){
        B=B%*%A   
      }
    }
    # remove border symmetry issues
    B=(1/2)*(t(B)+B)
    return(B)
}

II.2 Run a simulation

We can easily show that the discretization matrix \(\mathbf{A}\) of the differential operator is invertible. Regarding the precision matrix \(\mathbf{Q}\) of \(\mathbf{x}\) (i.e. the inverse of its covariance matrix of covariance), it is: \[\begin{align*} &\mathbf{A}\mathbf{x}=\tau\mathbf{z} \\ &\mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace \mathbf{A}\mathbf{x},\mathbf{A}\mathbf{x} \right\rbrace= \mathbf{A} \mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace \mathbf{x},\mathbf{x} \right\rbrace \mathbf{A}^\mathrm{T} = \mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace \tau\mathbf{z},\tau\mathbf{z} \right\rbrace \\ & \mathbf{A} \mathbf{\Sigma} \mathbf{A}^\mathrm{T} = \frac{\tau^2}{dxdy}\mathbf{I} \\ & \mathbf{\Sigma} = \frac{\tau^2}{dxdy} (\mathbf{A})^{-1} (\mathbf{A}^\mathrm{T})^{-1} \\ & \mathbf{Q} = \mathbf{\Sigma}^{-1} = \frac{dxdy}{\tau^2}\mathbf{A}^\mathrm{T}\mathbf{A} \end{align*}\]

A non-conditional simulation of state \(\mathbf{x}\) is obtained by solving the linear system introduced above for a random vector \(\mathbf{z}\) whose components are independent Gaussians of variance \(\tau^2/dxdy\).

# Raster-based image plot

  U[U<=zlim[1]]=zlim[1]
  U[U>=zlim[2]]=zlim[2]

  plot(ras,col=cmap,zlim=zlim)

    lag=1
    varexp=expVar(U,n0=Nx*Ny/2,lag = lag, nbpts = floor(0.6*Nx/lag),Nx,Ny,dx,dy)
    plot(varexp[,1],varexp[,2],type="l",ylim=c(0,1.2),xlab='h',ylab='gamma(h)')

}

# Discrete differential operator
A=DiffOperator(Nx,Ny,dx,dy,kappa)
B=pow_diff_operator(A,pow)

# Function to generate a non-conditional GRF simulation
## Inputs : 
## A: Discrete differential operator
## dx,dy : pas de la grille de travail
## Results
## Gaussian solution of discretized SPDE
simuNC<-function(A,dx,dy,tau){ 
  nbNodes=dim(A)[1]
  eps=(tau/sqrt(dx*dy))*rnorm(nbNodes,0,1)
  zc=solve(A,eps)
  return(zc) 
}

# Non conditional simulation

II.3 Kriging

Regarding optimal interpolation, let note \(\mathbf{y}\) the observations, the covariance matrix of \[\begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{y} \\ \mathbf{x} \end{bmatrix}\]

is: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{\Sigma} = \begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} \\ \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}} \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}\] with \(\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}}^\mathrm{T}=\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}}\)

The OI or simple kriging (with zero mean) of \(\mathbf{x}\) is given by: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{x}^\star = \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}^{-1} \mathbf{y} \end{align*}\] Its error covariance matrix is: \[\begin{align*} \mathrm{Cov}(\mathbf{x}^\star-\mathbf{x}) = \Sigma_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}} - \Sigma_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} \Sigma_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}^{-1} \Sigma_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} \end{align*}\]

We show that this formula can be rewritten: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{x}^\star = -\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}^{-1} \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} \mathbf{y} \end{align*}\] Indeed : \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{\Sigma} \mathbf{Q} = \begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} \\ \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}} \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} \\ \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{I}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{0}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} \\ \mathbf{0}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{I}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}} \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}\] Then, \[\begin{align*} &\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} + \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}}\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}} &= \mathbf{0}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}}\\ &\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}^{-1} + \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}^{-1}\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}}&= \mathbf{0}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}}\\ \end{align*}\] And by transposing: \[\begin{align*} & \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}^{-1} \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} + \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}^{-1}= \mathbf{0}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}}\\ & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}^{-1}=-\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}^{-1} \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} \end{align*}\]

Kriging \(\mathbf{x}^\star\) of \(\mathbf{y}\) is obtained by solving the linear system: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{x}^\star=-\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}^{-1}\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{y} \end{align*}\] and the error covariance matrix is: \[\begin{align*} \mathrm{Cov}(\mathbf{x}^\star-\mathbf{x}) = \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}^{-1} \end{align*}\]

This system is solved using Cholesky decomposition:

    1. We first compute \(\mathbf{L}\), the lower triangular Cholesky decomposition of \(\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x} \mathbf{x}}\): \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}=\mathbf{L}\mathbf{L}^\mathrm{T} \end{align*}\]
    1. We solve the linear system: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{L}\mathbf{X}=-\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{y} \end{align*}\]
    1. Then we solve the linear system: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{L}^\mathrm{T}\mathbf{x}^\star=\mathbf{X} \end{align*}\]

These two linear systems can be solved by substitution because the matrix \(\mathbf{L}\) is lower triangular. Regarding the complexity of the linear systems involved in kriging/OI, let make the following remarks:

  • In traditional geostatistics, we solve a system involving \(\Sigma_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}\) which has the size of the dataset
  • In the SPDE approach, we solve a system involving \(Q_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}\) which has the size of state space. However, \(\Sigma_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}\) is dense while \(Q_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}\) is sparse. In the latter, we can use algorithms adapted to sparse matrices of complexity \(\mathcal{O}(n^{3/2})\), while the general Cholesky algorithm is of complexity \(\mathcal{O}(n^{3})\).
# Generate a dataset
indexes_dat=NULL
for (j in 1:Ny){
    indexes_dat=c(indexes_dat,((Nx*(j-1))+10+j):(((Nx*(j-1))+10+j)+4))
    indexes_dat=c(indexes_dat,((Nx*(j-1))+10-j):(((Nx*(j-1))+10-j)-4))
}
indexes_dat=unique(indexes_dat[which(indexes_dat<=(Nx*Ny) & indexes_dat>0)])
# Target index (T)
indexes_tar = setdiff(1:(Nx*Ny),indexes_dat)
# Observation vector (ZD)
dat=Z[indexes_dat]
# Display
datPts=rep(NA,Nx*Ny)
datPts[indexes_dat]=dat
spplot(matrix(datPts,Nx),zlim=c(-2,2),title="Data")

# Function for Kriging/OI 
## Inputs:  
## VTT: Cholesky decomposition of QTT
## QTD: Submatrix QTD
## dat: observations
## indexes_dat : index for observations
## Results: 
## Interpolated values
krig_Chol<-function(VTT, QTD,dat,indexes_dat){
  ## Second member
  RM=-QTD%*%dat
  #### Permutation
  RM=expand(VTT)$P%*%RM
  ## Solve first Linear system
  zT_k =solve(VTT,RM,system="L")
  ## Solve second Linear system
  zT_k =solve(VTT,zT_k,system="Lt")
  ## Inverse Permutation
  zT_k = t(expand(VTT)$P)%*%zT_k
    
  nbNodes=dim(QTD)[1]+dim(QTD)[2]
  z_k=rep(NA,nbNodes)
  z_k[indexes_dat]=dat
  z_k[-indexes_dat]=zT_k
  return(z_k)
}

# Precision matrix Q
Q=(dx*dy)*t(B)%*%B
# Submatrix QTD
QTD=Q[indexes_tar,indexes_dat]
# Cholesky factorization of QTT
VTT = Cholesky(Q[indexes_tar,indexes_tar],perm=TRUE,LDL=FALSE)
# Kriging
z_k=krig_Chol(VTT,QTD,dat,indexes_dat)
# Display
spplot(matrix(Z,Nx),title="Ground Truth",zlim=c(-2,2))

spplot(matrix(z_k,Nx),zlim=c(-2,2),title="Kriging")
contour(1:Nx,1:Ny,is.na(matrix(datPts,nrow=Nx)),nlevels=1,add=T,lwd=2,col='red',drawlabels=FALSE)

II.4 Conditional simulation (by kriging)

Because OI acts by construction as a smoother of the hidden truth, an option to retrieve the original variability of the gaussian process is to run simulations conditionned by kriging. A simple though elegant solution in traditional geostatistics is to propose a conditional simulation \(\mathbf{x}_x\) to be equal to: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{x}_c (\mathbf{s}) = \mathbf{x}^\star(\mathbf{s}) + (\mathbf{x}_{nc}(\mathbf{s}) - \mathbf{x}^\star_{nc}(\mathbf{s})) \end{align*}\]

# Non conditional simulation #2
znc2=simuNC(B,dx,dy,tau)
# Non conditional simulation #3
znc3=simuNC(B,dx,dy,tau)
# Kriging of simulation #2
znc_k2=krig_Chol(VTT,QTD,znc2[indexes_dat],indexes_dat)
# Kriging of simulation #2
znc_k3=krig_Chol(VTT,QTD,znc3[indexes_dat],indexes_dat)
# Conditional simulation 
zc2=z_k+(znc2-znc_k2)
zc3=z_k+(znc3-znc_k3)
# Display
spplot(matrix(datPts,Nx),title="Data",zlim=c(-2,2))

spplot(matrix(Z,Nx),title="Ground Truth",zlim=c(-2,2))

spplot(matrix(zc2,Nx),title="Conditional simulation #1",zlim=c(-2,2))
contour(1:Nx,1:Ny,is.na(matrix(datPts,nrow=Nx)),nlevels=1,add=T,lwd=2,col='red',drawlabels=FALSE)

spplot(matrix(zc3,Nx),title="Conditional simulation #2",zlim=c(-2,2))
contour(1:Nx,1:Ny,is.na(matrix(datPts,nrow=Nx)),nlevels=1,add=T,lwd=2,col='red',drawlabels=FALSE)

III. Spatio-temporal extension

Let now consider the spatio-temporal extension to perform non-conditional simulations of a random field \(\mathbf{x}\) solution of the spatio-temporal SPDE: \[\begin{eqnarray} \label{isotropic_SPDE_st} \frac{\partial{\mathbf{X}}}{\partial{t}}+(\kappa^2(\mathbf{s},t)-\Delta)^{\alpha/2} \mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s},t)=\tau \mathbf{Z}(\mathbf{s},t) \end{eqnarray}\]

To ensure more regularity it is also possible to consider the noise process \(\mathbf{Z}\) be white in time but with spatial dependence, such as a solution to an isotropic spatial SPDE for instance: \[\begin{align*} & \mathbf{Z}(\mathbf{s},t) = \mathbf{Z}_T(t) \otimes \mathbf{W}_S(\mathbf{s}) \end{align*}\] with \[\begin{align} \label{isotropic_spatial_SPDE} & (\kappa_S^2 - \Delta)^{\alpha_S/2} \mathbf{W}_S(\mathbf{s}) = \mathbf{Z}_S(\mathbf{s}) \end{align}\]

This lead to the final model: \[\begin{eqnarray} \label{isotropic_SPDE_st_2} \frac{\partial{\mathbf{X}}}{\partial{t}}+(\kappa^2(\mathbf{s},t)-\Delta)^{\alpha/2} \mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s},t)=\tau \mathbf{Z}_T(t) \otimes \mathbf{W}_S(\mathbf{s}) \end{eqnarray}\]

We use a numerical implicit Euler scheme to discretize the space-time SPDE: \[\begin{eqnarray*} \frac{\mathbf{x}_{t+dt}-\mathbf{x}_{t}}{dt}+\mathbf{B}\mathbf{x}_{t+dt}=\frac{\tau}{\sqrt{dt}} \mathbf{w}_{t+dt} \end{eqnarray*}\]

where

  • \(\mathbf{x}_{t}\) the state space at time \(t\)
  • \(\mathbf{B}\) is still the discrete differential operator \((\kappa^2-\Delta)^{\alpha/2}\)
  • The random vectors \(\lbrace \mathbf{w}_t\), \(t>0 \rbrace\) are independent realizations of \(\mathbf{W}_S\) the solution of a spatial isotropic SPDE

Let now develop the relation between \(\mathbf{x}_{t+dt}\) using \(\mathbf{x}_{t}\) and \(\mathbf{z}_{t+dt}\) : \[\begin{align} \label{implicit_scheme} & \frac{\mathbf{x}_{t+dt}-\mathbf{x}_{t}}{dt}+\mathbf{B}_{t+dt}\mathbf{x}_{t+dt}&=&\frac{\tau}{\sqrt{dt}} \mathbf{w}_{t+dt} \nonumber \\ & \mathbf{x}_{t+dt}-\mathbf{x}_{t} + dt\mathbf{B}_{t+dt}\mathbf{x}_{t+dt}&=&\tau\sqrt{dt} \mathbf{w}_{t+dt} \nonumber \\ & (\mathbf{I}+dt\mathbf{B}_{t+dt})\mathbf{x}_{t+dt}&=&\mathbf{x}_{t}+\tau\sqrt{dt}\mathbf{w}_{t+dt} \nonumber \\ & \mathbf{x}_{t+dt} &=&(\mathbf{I}+dt\mathbf{B}_{t+dt})^{-1}(\mathbf{x}_{t}+\tau\sqrt{dt}\mathbf{w}_{t+dt}) \nonumber \\ & \mathbf{x}_{t+dt} &=& \mathbf{M}_{t+dt}(\mathbf{x}_{t}+\tau \sqrt{dt} \mathbf{w}_{t+dt}) & \end{align}\]

From now on, let denote \(\mathbf{M}_{t+dt}=(\mathbf{I}+dt\mathbf{B}_{t+dt})^{-1}\) the matrix operator to emulate the dynamical evolution of state \(\mathbf{x}\) from time \(t\) to \(t+dt\). It will ease the link with formal data assimilation state space formulation.

Fix the SPDE-based noise parameters

kappa_w = .33
A_w=DiffOperator(Nx,Ny,dx,dy,kappa_w)
pow_w=1              
alpha_w  = pow_w*2       
nu_w     = alpha_w-d/2   
tau_w=( (gamma(nu_w+d/2)*((4*pi)^(d/2))*(kappa^(2*nu_w))) / gamma(nu_w) )^(1/2)

III.1 Isotropy

III.1.a DF Discretized Laplacian

The discretized version of the Laplacian operator is the same that in the spatial case

# Discretized Laplacian (differential operator)
## Inputs :  
## Nx : number of points in direction x
## Ny : number of points in direction y
## dx : lag in direction x
## dy : lag in direction y
## Results :
## Sparse matrix with size (Nx*Ny)x(Nx*Ny) 

DiffOperator<-function(Nx,Ny,dx,dy, kappa){
  
  nbNodes=Nx*Ny
  indices=1:nbNodes
  

  # We start by creating an array containing the indices of the non-zero elements
  # of A with associated values and we will use the R function sparseMatrix 
  # to create A from this array

  # Right neighbour ( !! remove last column)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==0)]
  # Matrix values
  k1=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+1, -1/dx^2)
  
  # Left neighbour ( !! remove first column)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==1)]
  # Matrix values
  k2=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-1, -1/dx^2)
  
  # Top neighbour  ( !! remove last line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices>(Ny-1)*Nx)]
  # Matrix values
  k3=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+Nx, -1/dy^2)
  
  # Bottom neighbour ( !! remove first line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices<Nx+1)]
  # Matrix values
  k4=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-Nx, -1/dy^2)
  
  # Central point
  k5=cbind(indices,indices,kappa^2+2*(1/dx^2+1/dy^2))

  # Stack all neighbours
  k=rbind(k1,k2,k3,k4,k5)
  
  # Create sparseMatrix
  return(sparseMatrix(i=k[,1],j=k[,2],x=k[,3],dims = c(nbNodes,nbNodes)))
  
}

# Test function
A=DiffOperator(10,10,1,1,0)
image(A)

  ## Permutation

  ## Solve first Linear system

III.2 Global anisotropy

The Laplacian operator \(\Delta\) is invariant to translations and rotations. As a consequence, we will get an isotropic space-time field. Then, let introduce some diffusion process through a local diffusion operator \(\mathbf{H}(\mathbf{s},t)\) in the SPDE. In the case of global anisotropy, \(\mathbf{H}\) is constant over space and time:

\[\begin{eqnarray*} (\kappa^2-\nabla \cdot \mathbf{H}\nabla)^{\frac{\alpha}{2}}\mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s},t)=\tau\mathbf{Z}(\mathbf{s},t) \end{eqnarray*}\]

III.2.a DF Discretized Laplacian

DiffOperator2<-function(Nx,Ny,dx,dy,H,kappa){
  
  H11=H[1,1] ; H12=H[1,2] ; H21=H[2,1] ; H22=H[2,2]  
  nbNodes=Nx*Ny
  indices=1:nbNodes
  
  # Right neighbour ( !! remove last column)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==0)]
  # Matrix values
  k1=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+1, -H11/(dx^2))
    
  # Left neighbour ( !! remove first column)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==1)]
  # Matrix values
  k2=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-1, -H11/(dx^2))

  # Top neighbour  ( !! remove last line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices>(Ny-1)*Nx)]
  # Matrix values
  k3=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+Nx, -H22/(dy^2))
  
  # Bottom neighbour ( !! remove first line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices<(Nx+1))]
  # Matrix values
  k4=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-Nx, -H22/(dy^2))
        
  # Top-right neighbour ( !! remove last column & last line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==0 | indices>(Ny-1)*Nx)]
  # Matrix values
  k5=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+Nx+1, (H12+H21)/(4*dx*dy))
  
  # Top-left neighbour ( !! remove first column & last line)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==1  | indices>(Ny-1)*Nx)]
  # Matrix values
  k6=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+Nx-1, -(H12+H21)/(4*dx*dy))

  # Bottom-right neighbour ( !! remove last column & first line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==0 | indices<Nx+1)]
  # Matrix values
  k7=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-Nx+1, -(H12+H21)/(4*dx*dy))
  
  # Bottom-left neighbour ( !! remove first column & first line)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==1 | indices<Nx+1)]
  # Matrix values
  k8=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-Nx-1, (H12+H21)/(4*dx*dy))
    
  # Central point
  k9=cbind(indices,indices,kappa^2+2*(H11/(dx^2)+H22/(dy^2)))
    
  # Stack all neighbours
  k=rbind(k1,k2,k3,k4,k5,k6,k7,k8,k9)

  # Create sparseMatrix
  return(sparseMatrix(i=k[,1],j=k[,2],x=k[,3],dims = c(nbNodes,nbNodes)))
  
}

III.2.e Spatio-temporal kriging

To compute space-time OI along a data assimilation window \(\lbrace {\mathbf{y}_{t-Ldt},\cdots,\mathbf{y}_t}\rbrace\), we need to know how the process \(\mathbf{x}_t\) at current time \(t\) covariates with its past and future state. Then we are looking for \(\mathbf{\Sigma}_{t+kdt,t}\) (covariance between past time and current time) and \(\mathbf{\Sigma}_{t,t+kdt}\) (covariance between future time and current time).

According to Eq.(): \[\begin{align*} &\mathbf{\Sigma}_{t+dt,t}\\ &=\mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace \mathbf{x}_{t+dt},\mathbf{x}_{t} \right\rbrace\\ &=\mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace M_{t+dt}(\mathbf{x}_{t}+\tau dt\mathbf{z}_{t+dt}), \mathbf{x}_{t} \right\rbrace \\ &=M_{t+dt}\mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace \mathbf{x}_{t}+\tau dt\mathbf{z}_{t+dt}, \mathbf{x}_{t} \right\rbrace \\ &=M_{t+dt} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{t,t} \end{align*}\]

Then, \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{Q}_{t+dt,t} &= \mathbf{Q}_{t,t} \mathbf{M}_{t+dt}^{-1} \\ \mathbf{Q}_{t,t+dt} &= \mathbf{M}_{t+dt}^{-1} \mathbf{Q}_{t,t} \end{align*}\]

Looking for covariances between between any past time and current time, we have: \[\begin{align*} &\mathbf{\Sigma}_{t+2dt,t} \\ &=\mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace \mathbf{x}_{t+2dt},\mathbf{x}_{t} \right\rbrace \\ &=\mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace \mathbf{M}_{t+2dt}(\mathbf{x}_{t+dt}+\tau dt\mathbf{z}_{t+2dt}),\mathbf{x}_{t} \right\rbrace \\ &=\mathrm{Cov}\left\lbrace \mathbf{M}_{t+2dt}(\mathbf{M}_{t+dt}(\mathbf{x}_{t}+\tau dt\mathbf{z}_{t+dt}) +dt\mathbf{z}_{t+dt},\mathbf{x}_{t} \right\rbrace \\ &=\mathbf{M}_{t+2dt}\mathbf{M}_{t+dt} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{t,t} \end{align*}\]

Then, \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{Q}_{t+2dt,t} &= \mathbf{Q}_{t,t} \mathbf{M}_{t+dt}^{-1} \mathbf{M}_{t+2dt}^{-1} \\ \mathbf{Q}_{t,t+2dt} &= \mathbf{M}_{t+2dt}^{-1} \mathbf{M}_{t+dt}^{-1} \mathbf{Q}_{t,t} \end{align*}\]

Leading to the iterative recursion: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{Q}_{t+kdt,t} &= \mathbf{Q}_{t,t} \prod_{l=1}^{k} \mathbf{M}_{t+kdt}^{-1}\\ \mathbf{Q}_{t,t+kdt} &= \prod_{l=k}^{1} \mathbf{M}_{t+kdt}^{-1} \mathbf{Q}_{t,t} \end{align*}\]

Let note that if operator \(\mathbf{A}\) does not depend on time (then neither \(\mathbf{Q}\)), the recursion simplifies to: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{Q}_{t+kdt,t} &= \mathbf{Q} \mathbf{M}^{-k}\\ \mathbf{Q}_{t,t+kdt} &= \mathbf{M}^{-k} \mathbf{Q} \end{align*}\]

Also, the final model writes: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{t+dt} & = \mathbf{M}\mathbf{\Sigma}_t\mathbf{M}^{\mathrm{T}} + \tau^2 \mathbf{M}\mathbf{Q}(W)^{-1}\mathbf{M}^{\mathrm{T}} \end{align*}\]

The global covariance matrix of state sequences \(\lbrace \mathbf{x}_1,\cdots,\mathbf{x}_{Ldt} \rbrace\) writes: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{\Sigma}_G = \begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{\Sigma}_1 & \mathbf{\Sigma}_1 \mathbf{M}_2 & \mathbf{\Sigma}_1 \mathbf{M}_2 \mathbf{M}_3 & \cdots & \mathbf{\Sigma}_1 \prod_{l=1}^{L} \mathbf{M}_{t+ldt} \\ \mathbf{M}_2 \mathbf{\Sigma}_1 & \mathbf{\Sigma}_2 & \mathbf{\Sigma}_2 \mathbf{M}_3 & \cdots & \mathbf{\Sigma}_2 \prod_{l=2}^{L} \mathbf{M}_{t+ldt} \\ \mathbf{M}_3 \mathbf{M}_2 \mathbf{\Sigma}_1 & \mathbf{M}_3 \mathbf{\Sigma}_2 & \mathbf{\Sigma}_3 & \cdots & \vdots \\ \vdots & \vdots & \vdots & \ddots & \vdots \\ \prod_{l=L-1}^{2} \mathbf{M}_{t+ldt} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{1} & \vdots & \vdots & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{L-1} & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{L-1} \mathbf{M}_{t+Ldt} \\ \prod_{l=L}^{2} \mathbf{M}_{t+ldt} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{1} & \vdots & \vdots & \mathbf{M}_{t+Ldt} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{L-1} & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{L} \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}\]

and the precision matrix writes: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{Q}_G = \frac{1}{dt}[\mathbf{I}_{L} \otimes \mathbf{Q}(W)] \begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{M}^{-2} & -\mathbf{M}^{-1} & 0 & \cdots & 0 \\ -\mathbf{M}^{-1} & (\mathbf{M}^{-2}+\mathbf{I}) & -\mathbf{M}^{-1} & \cdots & \vdots \\ 0 & -\mathbf{M}^{-1} & (\mathbf{M}^{-2}+\mathbf{I}) & \cdots & 0 \\ \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & \cdots & -\mathbf{M}^{-1}\\ 0 & \cdots & 0 & -\mathbf{M}^{-1} & \mathbf{M}^{-2} \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}\]

itime=50

## Global covariance matrix
M    = Diagonal(nbNodes)+dt*B 
M2   = M%*%M
M2pI = M2+Diagonal(nbNodes)
M0   = Matrix(matrix(0,nrow=nbNodes,ncol=nbNodes),sparse=TRUE)
replicateM0 <-function(N){
  return(do.call(cbind, replicate(N, M0, simplify=FALSE)))
}

DAW=2
nbBlocks = 2*DAW+1

QR = ((dx*dy)/tau_w^2)*t(A_w)%*%(A_w)
QG = NULL
# first line
QG_ = cbind(M2%*%QR,-M%*%QR,replicateM0(nbBlocks-2))
QG  = rbind(QG,QG_)
# loop
for (i in 2:(nbBlocks-1)){
  QG_ = cbind(replicateM0(i-2),-M%*%QR,M2%*%QR,-M%*%QR,replicateM0(nbBlocks-3-(i-2)))
  QG  = rbind(QG,QG_)
}
# last line
QG_ = cbind(replicateM0(nbBlocks-2),-M%*%QR,M2%*%QR)
QG  = rbind(QG,QG_)
# force symmetry
QG  = 1/2*(t(QG)+QG)

dat=NULL
indexes_dat=NULL
cpt=0
for (k in seq(-DAW,DAW,1)) {
   # Index for Submatrix QTD of Qg
   indexes_dat=c(indexes_dat,idD[[itime+k]]+cpt*nbNodes)
   # space-time observations for kriging
   dat=c(dat,Z_data_all[itime+k,idD[[itime+k]]])
   cpt=cpt+1
}
# Index for Submatrix QTT of Qg
indexes_tar = setdiff(1:(nbNodes*nbBlocks),indexes_dat)
# Cholesky factorization of QTT
VTT = Cholesky(QG[indexes_tar,indexes_tar],perm=TRUE,LDL=TRUE)
# Submatrix QTD of Q
QTD=QG[indexes_tar,indexes_dat] 
# observation at t=itime
dat0=Z_data_all[itime,idD[[itime]]]
image(QTD)
krig_Chol_ST<-function(VTT, QTD,dat,indexes_dat,LDL=TRUE){
  ## Second member
  RM=-QTD%*%dat
  ## Permutation
  RM=expand(VTT)$P%*%RM
  ## Solve first Linear system
  zT_k =solve(VTT,RM,system="L")
  if(LDL==TRUE) {zT_k =solve(VTT,zT_k,system="D")} 
  ## Solve second Linear system
  zT_k =solve(VTT,zT_k,system="Lt")
  ## Inverse Permutation
  zT_k = t(expand(VTT)$P)%*%zT_k
  nbNodes_ST=dim(QTD)[1]+dim(QTD)[2]
  z_k=rep(NA,nbNodes_ST)
  z_k[indexes_dat]=dat
  z_k[-indexes_dat]=zT_k
  return(z_k)
}


# Spatio-temporal kriging
z_k_ST=krig_Chol_ST(VTT,QTD,dat,indexes_dat)[(DAW*nbNodes):(((DAW+1)*nbNodes)-1)]
znc=Z_all[itime,]
spplot(matrix(Z_data_all[itime,],nrow=Nx),zlim=c(-2,2),title='Data')

III.3 Local anisotropy

Let now introduce some local anisotropies. The underlying idea in this practical session would be to generate some artifical eddies.

\[\begin{eqnarray*} (\kappa^2-\nabla \cdot \mathbf{H}(\mathbf{s},t)\nabla)^{\frac{\alpha}{2}}\mathbf{X}(\mathbf{s},t)=\tau\mathbf{Z}(\mathbf{s},t) \end{eqnarray*}\]

III.1.a Anisotropy field

# Generate a periodic field to create some diffusion parameters
fxy<-function(x,y){
 return( ((2*resolution)/pi)*( (3/4)*sin(2*pi*x/(5*resolution))) + (1/4)*sin(2*pi*y/(5*resolution) ))
}
x=rep(1:Nx,Ny)

grad=gradient(res,1,1)
u_=grad$X
v_=grad$Y
rotate_vector<-function(x1,y1,angle){
  x1 = as.vector(x1)
  y1 = as.vector(y1)
  x2=cos(angle)*x1-sin(angle)*y1
  y2=sin(angle)*x1+cos(angle)*y1
  return(cbind(x2,y2))
}
u=matrix(rotate_vector(u_,v_,-pi/2)[,1],nrow=Nx)
v=matrix(rotate_vector(u_,v_,-pi/2)[,2],nrow=Nx)

# store all the diffusion parameters
library(abind)
Hs<-function(u,v,gamma,beta){
  nNodes = nrow(u)*ncol(u)
  H=array(NA,dim=c(2,2,nNodes))
  cpt=1
  for(i in 1:nrow(u)){
    for(j in 1:ncol(u)){
      vs=matrix(c(u[i,j],v[i,j]),nrow=2)
      Hs=(gamma*diag(2)) + beta*(vs%*%t(vs))
      H[,,cpt]=Hs
      cpt=cpt+1
    }
  }
  return(H)
}
Hs=Hs(u,v,1,25)

\[\begin{eqnarray} H(\mathbf{s})=\gamma \mathbf{I}_2 + \beta\left[\mathbf{v}(\mathbf{s}) \mathbf{v}(\mathbf{s})^\mathrm{T}\right] \end{eqnarray}\]

III.3.b DF Discretized Laplacian

DiffOperator3<-function(Nx,Ny,dx,dy,H,kappa){
  
  nbNodes=Nx*Ny
  indices=1:nbNodes
    
  # Right neighbour ( !! remove last column)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==0)]
  # Matrix values
  k1=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+1, -1*(H[1,1,indicesVoisins])/(dx^2))
  
  # Left neighbour ( !! remove first column)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==1)]
  # Matrix values
  k2=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-1, -1*(H[1,1,indicesVoisins])/(dx^2))

  # Top neighbour  ( !! remove last line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices>(Ny-1)*Nx)]
  # Matrix values
  k3=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+Nx, -1*(H[2,2,indicesVoisins])/(dy^2))
  
  # Bottom neighbour ( !! remove first line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices<(Nx+1))]
  # Matrix values
  k4=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-Nx, -1*(H[2,2,indicesVoisins])/(dy^2))
        
  # Top-right neighbour ( !! remove last column & last line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==0 | indices>(Ny-1)*Nx)]
  # Matrix values
  k5=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+Nx+1, H[1,2,indicesVoisins]/(2*dx*dy))
    
  # Top-left neighbour ( !! remove first column & last line)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==1  | indices>(Ny-1)*Nx)]
  # Matrix values
  k6=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins+Nx-1, -1*H[1,2,indicesVoisins]/(2*dx*dy))
    
  # Bottom-right neighbour ( !! remove last column & first line )
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==0 | indices<Nx+1)]
  # Matrix values
  k7=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-Nx+1, -1*H[1,2,indicesVoisins]/(2*dx*dy))
  
  # Bottom-left neighbour ( !! remove first column & first line)
  indicesVoisins=indices[-which(indices%%Nx==1 | indices<Nx+1)]
  # Matrix values
  k8=cbind(indicesVoisins,indicesVoisins-Nx-1, H[1,2,indicesVoisins]/(2*dx*dy))
    
  # Central point
  k9=cbind(indices,indices,kappa^2+2*(H[1,1,indices]/(dx^2)+H[2,2,indices]/(dy^2)))
    
  # Stack all neighbours
  k=rbind(k1,k2,k3,k4,k5,k6,k7,k8,k9)

  # Create sparseMatrix
  return(sparseMatrix(i=k[,1],j=k[,2],x=k[,3],dims = c(nbNodes,nbNodes)))
  
}

# Test function
A=DiffOperator3(10,10,1,1,Hs,0)
image(A)

        indexes_dat=c(indexes_dat,((Nx*(j-1))+10-j-(10*i%%Nx)):(((Nx*(j-1))+10-j-(10*i%%Nx)-4)))
    }
    indexes_dat=unique(indexes_dat[which(indexes_dat<=(Nx*Ny) & indexes_dat>0)])
    Z2_data_all[i,-indexes_dat]=NA
}

V. Perspectives

General idea: * use NN for parameter estimation \(\kappa(\mathbf{s},t), \mathbf{m}(\mathbf{s},t), \mathbf{H}(\mathbf{s},t)\) given the available data \(\mathbf{y}_{1:Ldt}\) of the SPDE * generate ensemble of conditional SPDE * find the best weighting of the ensemble (hybrid DA)

V.I. Strategy #1: Use spatio-temporal conditional simulations

V.II. Strategy #2: A formal link with (En)KF

In the end, we want an analysis \(\mathbf{x}^a_{k}\) given by: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{x}^a_{k} & = \mathbf{x}^f_{k} + \mathbf{u}_{k} \end{align*}\] where \(\mathbf{u}_{k+1}\) denotes a correction term, which finds the optimal compromise between the observations and the model prior. From a geostatistical perspective, the optimal way of estimating \(\mathbf{u}_{k}=\mathbf{x}^a_{k}-\mathbf{x}^f_{k}\) is given by: \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{u}^\star_{k}=\mathbf{K}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} \left(\mathbf{y}_k - \mathbf{H}_k \mathbf{x}_k \right) \end{align*}\] with \(\mathbf{K}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}}\) the matrix of optimal weights of size \(m \times p_k\) and \(\left(\mathbf{y}_k - \mathbf{H}_k (\mathbf{x}_k) \right)\) are the innovations. The matrix \(\mathbf{K}\) is obtained by minimization of the estimation variance $$ leading to the so-called BLUE/(simple) kriging equations : \[\begin{align*} \mathbf{K}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} & = \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}}\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}^{-1} \end{align*}\] where, regarding the covariance-based equation we have \(\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}}\) the covariance of the innovations and \(\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}}\) the empirical cross-covariance matrices between \(\mathbf{x}^f\) and \(\mathbf{H}(\mathbf{x}^f)\) that writes: \[\begin{align*} &\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}} = E \left \lbrace \mathbf{d} \mathbf{d}^{\mathrm{T}} \right \rbrace &=& \mathbf{H}_k \mathbf{P}_k^f \mathbf{H}_k^{\mathrm{T}} + \mathbf{R} \\ &\mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} = E \left \lbrace \mathbf{x}^f \left(\mathbf{H}\mathbf{x}^f\right)^{\mathrm{T}} \right \rbrace &=& \mathbf{P}_k^f \mathbf{H}_k^{\mathrm{T}}, \end{align*}\]

Going back to the global precision matrix, it writes: \[\begin{align} \label{covariance_OI_KF} \mathbf{\Sigma} = \begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} \\ \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{\Sigma}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}} \end{bmatrix} = =\begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{H}_k \mathbf{P}_k^f \mathbf{H}_k^{\mathrm{T}} + \mathbf{R} & \mathbf{H}_k \mathbf{P}_k^f \\ \mathbf{P}_k^f \mathbf{H}_k^{\mathrm{T}} & \mathbf{P}_k^f \end{bmatrix} \end{align}\]

\[\begin{align*} \mathbf{Q} =\begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{y}\mathbf{x}} \\ \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} & \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}} \end{bmatrix} = \begin{bmatrix} \mathbf{R}_k^{-1} & -\mathbf{R}_k^{-1}\mathbf{H}_k \\ -\mathbf{H}_k^{\mathrm{T}}\mathbf{R}_k^{-1} & \mathbf{Q}^f_k+ \mathbf{H}_k^{\mathrm{T}}\mathbf{R}_k^{-1}\mathbf{H}_k \end{bmatrix} \end{align*}\] where \(\mathbf{Q}^f_k\) is nothing else than the precision matrix of state \(\mathbf{x}_k\) at time \(t_k\). This leads to the precision-based formulation of the Kalman Filter: \[\begin{align} \mathbf{x}^a_{k} & = \mathbf{x}^f_{k} -\mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{x}}^{-1} \mathbf{Q}_{\mathbf{x}\mathbf{y}} \left( \mathbf{y}_k - \mathbf{H}_k (\mathbf{x}_k) \right) \nonumber \\ & = \mathbf{x}^f_{k} + \left( \mathbf{Q}^f_k+ \mathbf{H}^{\mathrm{T}}\mathbf{R}^{-1}\mathbf{H} \right)^{-1} \mathbf{H}^{\mathrm{T}}\mathbf{R}^{-1} \left( \mathbf{y}_k - \mathbf{H}_k \mathbf{x}_k \right) \end{align}\] In a classic DA formulation, this type of formulation is not interesting because \(\left( \mathbf{Q}^f_k+ \mathbf{H}_k^{\mathrm{T}}\mathbf{R}_k^{-1}\mathbf{H}_k \right)^{-1}\) lies in state space and is not sparse. But within an SPDE-based formulation of \(\mathbf{Q}^f_k\), Cholesky algorithm can again be involved to solve for the analysis step. In addition, it directly relates the precision matrix involved in the spatio-temporal simulation with the precision-based formulation of the Kalman gain.\
